                                    <div class="row  mt-4 mb-0 mb-md-4">
                        <div class="col-12 col-md-6">
                            <aside class="author-name">
                                    
    
                                    
            By <a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/staff/kevin-lincoln">Kevin Lincoln</a>
                                    
                                <div class="mt-1">
                                    <span class="can-localize">September 24, 2009 | 4:00am EDT</span>
                                </div>
                            </aside>
                        </div>
                        <div class="col-12 col-md-6 text-left text-md-right d-print-none">
                            <ul class="social-links list-unsyled list-inline mt-4 mt-md-0">
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="http://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2009/09/saturn-sun-ra-arkesta-prepares-page" target="_blank" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="facebook" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fab fa-facebook"></i></a></li>
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="http://twitter.com/intent/tweet?url=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2009/09/saturn-sun-ra-arkesta-prepares-page&amp;text=From Saturn, Sun Ra Arkesta prepares for Page" target="_blank" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="twitter" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fab fa-twitter"></i></a></li>
                                                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="mailto:?subject=From%20Saturn%2C%20Sun%20Ra%20Arkesta%20prepares%20for%20Page%20|%20The%20Chronicle&amp;message=Check%20out%20this%20article%20from%20The%20Chronicle%3A%20https%3A%2F%2Fwww.dukechronicle.com%2Farticle%2F2009%2F09%2Fsaturn-sun-ra-arkesta-prepares-page" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="email" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fa fa-envelope"></i></a></li>
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="#" onclick="window.print()" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="facebook" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fas fa-print"></i></a></li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                
                <div class="article-content w-100 mb-4">
                                            <p>&nbsp;Taking the reins of a jazz band numbering over a dozen musicians is challenging enough. But Marshall Allen faced a unique obstacle after eventually replacing the deceased Sun Ra as director of his eponymous Arkestra.</p>
<p>&ldquo;The whole band left the planet,&rdquo; Allen said.</p>

                        <div class="inline-ad float-none float-md-left my-4 mr-0 mr-md-4 text-center d-print-none">
                            <!-- START gryphon/ads/rectangle-inline.tpl -->
            <div id="azk18664"></div>
    <!-- END gryphon/ads/rectangle-inline.tpl -->
                        </div>

                        <p>This is just another aspect of the Sun Ra mythology, as told by an Alabama musician born Herman Poole Blount, legally named Le Sony&rsquo;r Ra and commonly regarded as one of the most influential jazz composers ever.&nbsp;</p>
<p>It isn&rsquo;t the unique backstory that will be on display, however, when the Arkestra comes to Page Auditorium this Saturday, featured on a double bill with the Mingus Big Band. It&rsquo;s the revolutionary avant-garde take on American music that will come center stage. This abrasive and exotically futuristic wielding of the big band format has exerted an inestimable influence on Ra&rsquo;s contemporaries and disciples.&nbsp;</p>
<p>The last five decades have seen the Arkestra work in the midst of an aggressively evolving musical landscape, but Allen is able to offer a concise evaluation of what&rsquo;s different for the group since he joined 51 years ago.</p>
<p>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s changed because Sun Ra&rsquo;s not here,&rdquo; he said.</p>
<p>The founder&rsquo;s presence is still a tangible and vital aspect of the group despite his death&mdash;or his &ldquo;ascension,&rdquo; in band lore&mdash;in 1993. Shows involve a substantial amount of his compositions, and the theatrical tradition of performing in colorful costumes is one he originated.</p>
<p>&nbsp;&ldquo;We like to tell a story, different ages of music, you know,&rdquo; Allen said. &ldquo;Fletcher Henderson, Duke Ellington, &lsquo;Count&rsquo; Basie, we play some of those things, old stomps and things. We play modern arrangements, we play Sun Ra originals and I play my originals too. And then we play avant-garde and all the rest&mdash;mix it all up.&rdquo;</p>

                        <div class="inline-ad float-none float-md-left my-4 mr-0 mr-md-4 text-center d-print-none">
                            <!-- START gryphon/ads/rectangle-article-5.tpl -->
        <div id="azk5125"></div>
<!-- END gryphon/ads/rectangle-article-5.tpl -->
                        </div>

                                                                            <p>The Arkestra has always been cognizant of the artistic atmosphere it existed within, and the group hasn&rsquo;t lost this awareness in its current stage. Along with the Mingus Big Band, the two outfits are able to use their legacies and abundant technical skills to articulate a past, present and future of music.</p>
<p>&ldquo;You&rsquo;ll have these two different musical languages, both existing within jazz, both related to the roots of a sound, but also then both pushing boldly forward,&rdquo; said Aaron Greenwald, director of Duke Performances. &ldquo;My thought would be as they push forward and reference the past, you&rsquo;ll see a bunch of places where they overlap.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>
<p>The Arkestra&rsquo;s performances are in accordance with this dedication to something beyond; they encompass a visual aesthetic that allows the instrumentalists&rsquo; wardrobes and the use of color to alter the aural experience. &nbsp;</p>
<p>This link to visual art makes even more sense when seen in the light of the paintings, costumes and similar artifacts Sun Ra left behind, all currently on display at CCB Gallery downtown.&nbsp;</p>
                            

<div class="mc-signup my-4 p-4 text-center " id="mc-container" data-mc="fdab49f43c">
    <h3>Get The Dirt</h3>
    <p>Subscribe to our weekly email about what&#039;s trending at Duke</p>
