            </form>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
                        
                        <p>&ldquo;There&rsquo;s this synergy with the exhibition of the Durham Arts Guild, which is really a pretty massive exhibition, pretty critically acclaimed and a real coup for the Arts Guild to get,&rdquo; Greenwald said. &ldquo;So, it seemed like there was going to be a campus-wide, if not community-wide, conversation around Sun Ra and the Arkestra that we wanted to participate in&hellip;. [The exhibition] gives you the visual angle on the Sun Ra universe.&rdquo;</p>
<p>But despite the intricate layering of music, mythology and visual and performance art, the serially inflected jazz of the band still astounds in its own right. And it speaks wonders to the sheer competence of Sun Ra and his successors that they managed to convey his unique vision and maintain such an unwieldy apparatus as a big band for so many years.&nbsp;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Both Sun Ra and Charles Mingus are ideal examples of folks who have created new, bold music and, in Sun Ra&rsquo;s case, a bold mythology that centers on a certain modernism,&rdquo; Greenwald said. &ldquo;There&rsquo;s a newness to what they&rsquo;re creating, a sense of imagining what the future of jazz or African-American music in general sounds like.&rdquo;</p>
<p>The community is certainly recognizing the Arkestra&rsquo;s importance, but for Allen, the band&rsquo;s mission can be stated far more simply. &nbsp;</p>
<p>&ldquo;We come down there to play.&rdquo;</p>

